"The sea is ours": Bolivia, without coastline, expects the court to reopen the path to the Pacific
The sailors patrol their ship covered with bark in La Paz.
Public buildings wave a blue sea flag.
The naval bases from Lake Titicaca to Amazons are enthralled by the motto: "The sea is ours by right.
Recovering it is a duty."
Across Bolivia's land without coastline, the memory of a lost coastline in Chile in a conflict of resources in the 19th century remains very vivid, as is the yearning to sail again across the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes are perhaps the deepest in decades, while Bolivia awaits the resolution that the International Court of Justice will issue on October 1 after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has the impulse, a spirit of unity and serenity, and, no need to say, waits with a positive stance for the result," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will look at the resolution of the TIJ on large screens across the country, hoping that the Hague Court will dictate in favour of Bolivia's claim that, after decades of intermittent conversations, Chile is obliged to negotiate the concession of a sovereign exit to the sea for Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president, who faces a controversial battle for re-election next year, also has many hopes laid down in Monday's resolution.
"We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean," he promised last August.
However, some analysts believe that it is unlikely that the Court would decide in favour of Bolivia and that if it did, things would not change much.
The United Nations agency based in the Netherlands has no power to award Chile and has established that it will not determine the outcome of possible talks.
The resolution of the TIJ, which takes place only six months after the final submissions are made, indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Peace Zárate, Chilean specialist in international law.
And far from seeing yourself in favor, Bolivia's cause may have experienced a backlog in the last four years.
"The current Bolivian administration has kidnapped the issue of access to the sea," Zárate pointed out.
"The belligerent rhetoric of Morales has affected any gesture of good will by Chile," he suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be very difficult to keep conversations after this episode.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, representative of Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the idea that the Tribunal's decision-making was exceptionally rapid.
Next Monday Bolivia will have "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and an opportunity to "put an end to 139 years of discrepancies, with mutual benefits," he said.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who remains one of the most popular presidents of Latin America, was using the maritime issue as a political cross.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific Ocean," he added.
"The resolution is an opportunity to realize that we must overcome the past."
