John Edward: Language skills are essential for world citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a course of academic excellence that continued in 2018 with another series of excellent exam results, which is enhanced with individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With more than 30,000 students all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (CIS), are working to offer a service of the best level to students and parents.
The purpose of independent schools is to prepare students for further and higher education, for their career and for their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a custom school curriculum, we note that modern languages remain a matter of highly popular and desirable choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: “If you speak a man in a language that he understands, you’ll get to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart."
This is a very important reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
From the recent results of the reviews of this year, we can see that languages lead the classification tables with the highest qualifications in independent schools.
68% of students studying foreign languages obtained the A superior score.
Data collected from 74 ISIS member schools reflected that 72% of students obtained A superior qualification in Mandarin, while 72% of German students, 69% of French students, and 63% of Spanish students also obtained an A.
This demonstrates that Scotland's independent schools support foreign languages as vital competences that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Today, languages, as a subject of choice, are kept in the same consideration as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey conducted by the United Kingdom Employment and Skills Commission revealed that 17% of the reasons given by entrepreneurs for the fact that it was difficult to cover vacancies were attributed to the lack of language skills.
Thus, language skills are increasingly needed to prepare young people for their future careers.
Since there are more and more potential job opportunities that require languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of a person’s choice of a career, having learned a second language, he or she will have a real advantage in the future with such a permanent skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts a multilingual person in front of competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGov among more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation, and the French, with 15% speakers, was the only language with a double digit percentage.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is important for children today.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developed economies, will give children better opportunities to find important work.
In Scotland there is diversity between schools in the languages they teach.
Some schools focus more on more traditional modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered to be more important for the United Kingdom in the future by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your son's interest is, he'll always be able to choose between a series of languages in independent schools, which have staff teaching specialists in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the necessary skills to succeed, regardless of what the future may be.
In today's global trading environment, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be of vital importance to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as "international communicative competences".
Independent schools will continue to offer this option, diversity and excellence to young Scottish people.
We've got to do it right.
John Edward is director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
