North Korea declares that it will not be unilaterally disarmed "in any way" if no signs of trust are appreciated
The North Korean Foreign Minister informed the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions were intensifying their distrust in the United States and that under such circumstances the country would not unilaterally eliminate its nuclear weapons in any way.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Organization's Annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant measures of good will” during the previous year, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear testing centre and committing itself to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we do not observe any responses in consonance with the United States," he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security and, under these circumstances, we will not begin disarmament unilaterally in any way."
While Ri resumed the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a phased-out denuclearization approach for which North Korea would be rewarded as he gradually took action, his statements seemed significant because he did not reject the unilateral denuclearization of the whole, as Pyongyang had already done in the past.
Ri referred to the joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a US President and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, in which Kim pledged to work on the "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea has tried to formally end the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has reported that Pyongyang must first eliminate its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted the call to relax the harsh international sanctions imposed in North Korea.
"The United States insists that denuclearisation must first occur and increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve its objective in a coercive manner, in addition to opposing the "war-end declaration," said Ri.
"The perception that sanctions will make us kneel is a burning of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that continued sanctions are intensifying our distrust."
Ri did not refer to plans to hold a second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader highlighted in the United Nations at the beginning of the week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the part involved in the denuclearization issue were South Korea instead of the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this stagnation situation."
However, the tone of Ri's speech was very different from what he held last year, when he declared to the UN General Assembly that pointing to the U.S. territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after President "Mr. Evil" Trump named Kim from "Rocket Man" on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for her courage to take disarmament measures, but said that much remains to be done and sanctions must be maintained until North Korea is denuclearized.
Last Wednesday, Trump said there was no deadline for this and "it doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months."
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should award Pyongyang for the measures taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo declared on Thursday to the UN Security Council: “The enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without exception until we confirm complete and definitive denuclearisation.”
The Security Council has led sanctions in North Korea unanimously since 2006 on a bet to cut the funding of Pyongyang's ballistic and nuclear missile programmes.
Pompeo met Ri outside the UN General Assembly and then reported that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip did not go very well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying that progress had been made, but within a few hours North Korea accused him of making “own demands of a gangster.”
At a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile centre and a nuclear complex if the United States took “consonance measures”.
He said that Kim had told him that the "consonance measures" he was looking for were the security measures Trump had promised in Singapore, in addition to actions towards normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on rest habits
This year, a new course at Harvard University has allowed its students to sleep more, in an attempt to fight the growing culture of studying all night, stimulated by caffeine.
One scholar observed that students at number one university in the world are often dismissed from basics about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of Sound Medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of his species in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after giving a talk about the impact sleep deprivation had on learning.
"At the end of the talk, a girl approached me and said, "Why are you telling me now, all this, in my last year?"
He said no one had ever talked to him about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he reported to the newspaper The Telegraph.
In the course, implemented for the first time this year, the students are told the basic concepts about how good sound habits improve academic and sports performance in addition to general well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the University, said that the University decided to introduce the course after learning that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course, one hour long, includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section there is an image of a dorm, where students have to click on cups of coffee, curtains, bamboos and books to receive information about the effects of caffeine and light, about how sports performance affects sleeplessness, and about the importance of keeping a routine to go to sleep.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
Below is a map of the campus with interactive icons that encourages participants to think about its daily route.
“ We know that students’ conduct will not change immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know, as one has the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes," said Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride of staying awake all night still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and increasing pressure from students make sleep deprivation an increasing problem.
Making sure to enjoy a good-quality sleep for long enough should be a "secret weapon" of students to combat stress, fatigue and anxiety, added, even to avoid gaining weight, as the deprivation of sleep puts the brain in mode of inanition and makes students always hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of Physical Chemistry and Biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after attending one of his classes in the last year of his first year at Harvard.
Raymond commented that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote the course throughout the campus.
The next step, he expects, is to ask postgraduate students to conduct a similar study program before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students take into account the fact that they are alarmed when they go to sleep and when they wake up, and that they are aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can alter the harmony of the circaday rhythm and cause sleep problems.
