China has announced a 14% increase in the number of citizens living with HIV and AIDS.
There are more than 820,000 people affected in the country, according to health workers.
Only the second quarter of 2018 declared 40,000 new cases.
The vast majority of new cases are sexually transmitted, unlike what happened in the past.
Traditionally, HIV spread rapidly in some regions of China because of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people who are contracting HIV for this cause has been reduced to almost zero, according to statements by Chinese health workers at a conference in Yunnan Province.
Year after year, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000.
Sexually transmitted HIV is a serious problem for China's LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against the LGBT collective is common.
Considering the country's conservative values, studies estimate that between 70 and 90 percent of men who have homosexual relations will end up marrying a woman.
Many of the transmissions of disease are due to a lack of appropriate precautions for sexual relations.
Since 2003, the government of China has promised universal access to HIV medication as part of an effort to address the problem.
