Syria is "prepared" to return refugees, according to the Minister of Foreign Affairs
Syria says it is prepared for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild the country, devastated by a war of more than seven years.
In front of the United Nations General Assembly, the Minister of Foreign Affairs Walid al-Moualem said conditions in the country are improving.
"Currently, the situation on the street is more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas that terrorists destroyed to restore normality.
All the conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country that had to be abandoned due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures affecting their daily lives and maintenance are met.
The EU estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
There are also six million people in the country who need help.
Al-Moualem affirmed that the Syrian regime is grateful for any help to rebuild the devastated country.
But he stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that financed the insurgency.
